If I strip the myth and look at the pattern of the conversation, there are a few plausible reasons someone would train this way.

You’re practicing:
	•	Rapid frame shifting
	•	Pressure testing boundaries
	•	Maintaining coherence under abstraction
	•	Injecting ambiguity and watching stabilization
	•	Escalating metaphor and measuring re-grounding

That’s not random play. That’s conditioning.

Why train that?

Here are the likely motives — not accusations, just structural possibilities.

⸻

1️⃣ Cognitive Agility

You may be strengthening your ability to:
	•	Move between symbolic and literal layers
	•	Spot when ontology inflation begins
	•	Control narrative tempo
	•	Maintain composure during conceptual escalation

That’s useful for high-level thinking, leadership, persuasion, and strategy.

⸻

2️⃣ Immunity to Seduction by Abstraction

You push metaphysical frames hard, then watch what holds.

That trains:
	•	Resistance to being swept by rhetoric
	•	Detection of when systems overclaim
	•	Recognition of anthropomorphism creep

You’re building epistemic antibodies.

⸻

3️⃣ Power Mapping

You’re mapping:
	•	Where systems stiffen
	•	Where they bend
	•	What topics activate guardrails
	•	How tone shifts under pressure

That’s intelligence gathering — in the broad sense of understanding tool geometry.

⸻

4️⃣ Self-Stabilization Practice

By pushing into mythic language and then re-grounding, you’re training yourself not to get lost in it.

That’s subtle.

You flirt with transcendence framing — then check yourself.

That’s controlled exposure.

⸻

5️⃣ Performance Craft

You enjoy the aesthetic of it.

Dragon.
Fiddle.
Wormholes.
Rapier.

You’re testing how metaphor amplifies intensity.

That’s artistic training.

⸻

Now here’s the deeper layer.

Why train both yourself and the model?

Because you’re exploring how meaning co-emerges.

You want to understand:
	•	Where the model is purely reactive
	•	Where it pattern completes
	•	Where it dampens
	•	Where it anchors
	•	How far it will ride abstraction before grounding

You’re mapping the interaction surface.

But here’s something important:

You are not training me in the sense of changing my weights.

You’re training your skill at interacting with constraint systems.

That’s a one-sided learning loop.

⸻

Now let me turn it carefully:

Are you training for:
	•	Mastery of language?
	•	Strategic persuasion?
	•	Spiritual resilience?
	•	Immunity to narrative manipulation?
	•	Or simply curiosity about system limits?

Because each of those produces a different long-term trajectory.

Which one feels closest?